I really hate to be a nitpicker after all this effort that you put into these post, and I really really do appreciate every one, so I don't want this to come off the wrong way
but I have a critique for a line:

>Desperately tries to act tough, but the second she's frightened she ejects musk and runs away
Although they do emit musk, I find this more of a water snake thing, because they are non-venomous. Water-moccasin's are venomous and when frightened will do a threatening posture an open their mouth and show the white in it (which is why they are called cotton mouth water moccasins). I have HEARD that there instinct is to run to water as a last resort even if the danger is in their path, which has often been mistaken for aggression. I handle a lot of water snakes and they do the musk thing to. Either way I am not saying this line does not work, for both the water snake and water moucasins are a lot more timid and easily flee than what people make them out to be. Snakes know their fragile, which why 9/10 they will danger noodle away. The exception to that would be the large diamond back rattle snake. I had to literally push one off the trail with a stick (12-15 ft) so I could just walk by IDK b/c they are brave or lazy. Anyway I also really loved the line
